Tutorial on using Seaborn for Visualisation

By Mahaprasad Mohanty [24MDT0061]

Seaborn is a Python visualization library based on matplotlib. It provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive statistical graphics.

Installation

pip install seaborn

Usecases and types of plots

Before diving in, make sure you have the following libraries installed.

In[1]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

1. Scatterplot

When to use scatterplots?

  • To examine relationship between 2 continous variables
  • To identify correlations and patterns
  • Detecting outliers

Common applications

  • Stock price v/s trading volume relation
  • Height v/s weight studies
  • Temperature v/s energy consumption studies, etc

Key Parameters used

  • x, y: Variables that specify the coordinates
  • hue: Variable for color encoding
  • size: Variable for size encoding
  • style: Variable for shape encoding
  • data: Input dataset (DataFrame)

Example

In[2]:
np.random.seed(42)
n_points = 100
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'x': np.random.normal(0, 1, n_points),
    'y': np.random.normal(0, 1, n_points),
    'category': np.random.choice(['A', 'B', 'C'], n_points)
})
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='x', y='y', hue='category')
plt.title('Simple Scatter Plot with Categories')
plt.show()
In[]:

2. Lineplot

When to use lineplots?

  • Showing trends over time
  • Comparing multiple time series
  • Visualizing continuous relationships

Common Applications

  • Time series data
  • Sequential numerical data
  • Multiple series with a common x-axis

Key Parameters used

  • x, y: Variables for the line coordinates
  • hue: Grouping variable for multiple lines
  • orient: x or y
  • estimator: Method for aggregating multiple y values at same x value

Example

In[3]:
flights = sns.load_dataset("flights")
flights.head()

# using long form data
may_flights = flights.query("month == 'May'")
sns.lineplot(data=may_flights, x="year", y="passengers")
Out[3]:
<Axes: xlabel='year', ylabel='passengers'>
In[5]:
# for wide-form representation
flights_wide = flights.pivot(index="year", columns="month", values="passengers")
flights_wide.head()

# plotting a single vector and passing it to data
sns.lineplot(data=flights_wide["May"])
Out[5]:
<Axes: xlabel='year', ylabel='May'>
In[6]:
# passing the entire wide-form dataset

sns.lineplot(data=flights_wide)
Out[6]:
<Axes: xlabel='year'>
In[]:

3. Histplot

When to use?

  • to understand distribution of single variable
  • checking for normality
  • Identify the modes and skewness

Common Applications

  • Age distributions
  • Income distributions
  • Response times

Key parameters used

  • data: Input array or variable
  • bins: Number of bins or bin edges
  • kde: Whether to overlay a kernel density estimate
  • stat: Statistic to compute ('count', 'frequency', 'density', 'probability')

Example

In[8]:
penguins = sns.load_dataset("penguins")
sns.histplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm")
Out[8]:
<Axes: xlabel='flipper_length_mm', ylabel='Count'>
In[10]:
# plotting on the y axis
sns.histplot(data=penguins, y="flipper_length_mm")
Out[10]:
<Axes: xlabel='Count', ylabel='flipper_length_mm'>
In[11]:
# modifying the bin width
sns.histplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", bins=30)
Out[11]:
<Axes: xlabel='flipper_length_mm', ylabel='Count'>

4. Boxplots

When to use

  • Comparing distributions across categories
  • Identifying outliers
  • Showing summary statistics (median, quartiles)

Common Applications

  • Salary distributions by department
  • Product measurements by batch
  • Student performance by class

Key Parameters used

  • x: Categorical variable
  • y: Continuous variable
  • hue: Additional categorical variable for nested boxplots
  • whis: Whisker length as a multiple of the IQR
  • orient: Orientation of the plot (v | h | x | y)

Examples

In[13]:
titanic = sns.load_dataset("titanic")
sns.boxplot(x=titanic["age"])
Out[13]:
<Axes: xlabel='age'>
In[15]:
# Group by a categorical variable, referencing columns
sns.boxplot(data=titanic, x="age", y="class")
Out[15]:
<Axes: xlabel='age', ylabel='class'>
In[16]:
# vertical boxplot with nested grouping
sns.boxplot(data=titanic, x="class", y="age", hue="alive")
Out[16]:
<Axes: xlabel='class', ylabel='age'>

5. Heatmaps

When to use?

  • Visualizing correlation matrices
  • Displaying confusion matrices
  • Showing complex relationships between multiple variables

Common Applications

  • Feature correlation in machine learning
  • Customer behavior patterns
  • Performance metrics across time periods

Key Parameters used

  • data: 2D dataset that can be coerced into a DataFrame
  • annot: If True, writes values inside cells
  • cmap: Color map for the heatmap
  • center: Value at which to center the colormap
  • vmin, vmax: Values to anchor the colormap

Examples

In[19]:
# Generate correlated data
np.random.seed(42)
data = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(100, 5), columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E'])
data['B'] = data['A'] + np.random.randn(100) * 0.3
data['C'] = -data['A'] + np.random.randn(100) * 0.3

correlation = data.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(correlation, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix Heatmap')
plt.show()
In[21]:
glue = sns.load_dataset("glue").pivot(index="Model", columns="Task", values="Score")

# adding lines between cells
sns.heatmap(glue, annot=True, linewidth=.5)
Out[21]:
<Axes: xlabel='Task', ylabel='Model'>

6. KDE Plots

When to use?

  • Visualizing continuous probability distributions
  • Comparing smooth distributions
  • Identifying modes and skewness

Common Applications

  • Population density analysis
  • Probability distribution modeling
  • Signal processing visualization

Key Parameters used

  • data: Input data
  • bw_adjust: Factor to scale the bandwidth
  • fill: If True, fills the space under the curve
  • cumulative: If True, plots the cumulative distribution
  • palette: Method for choosing the colors
  • hue_order: pecify the order of processing and plotting for categorical levels

Examples

In[29]:
# a univariate distribution along the x axis
tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")
sns.kdeplot(data=tips, x="total_bill");
In[27]:
# distributions for each column of a wide-form datase
iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
sns.kdeplot(data=iris);
In[30]:
# using less smoothing
sns.kdeplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", bw_adjust=.2)
Out[30]:
<Axes: xlabel='total_bill', ylabel='Density'>

7. Pairplot

When to use?

  • Exploring relationships between multiple variables
  • Initial data exploration
  • Finding correlations in multivariate data

Common Applications

  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  • Feature selection for machine learning
  • Scientific measurement correlations

Key Parameters used

  • data: DataFrame with variables to plot
  • hue: Variable for color encoding
  • diag_kind: Kind of plot for diagonal ('hist', 'kde')
  • plot_kws: Additional plotting keywords
  • pallete: Set of colors for mapping the hue variable.

Examples

In[33]:
penguins = sns.load_dataset("penguins")
sns.pairplot(penguins);
In[35]:
# Assigning a hue variable adds a semantic mapping and changes the default marginal plot to a layered kernel density estimate
sns.pairplot(penguins, hue="species");
In[36]:
# The kind parameter determines both the diagonal and off-diagonal plotting style
sns.pairplot(penguins, kind="kde")
Out[36]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x2b3c6feae00>

8. Violin plots

When to use?

  • Comparing distributions across multiple categories
  • Identifying multimodal distributions (multiple peaks)
  • Showing the full shape of data distribution

Common applications

  • Violin plots can be used to compare the peaks, valleys.
  • can show the presence of different peaks, their position
  • can visualize the entire distribution of the data, including the tails, which might not be visible in a box plot.

Key parameters

  • data:DataFrame containing the data
  • x : Category variable or vector data
  • y: Value variable or vector data
  • hue: Variable for splitting violins
  • order: Order of categorical variables
  • scale: The method used to scale the width

Examples

In[38]:
sns.catplot(
    data=tips, x="total_bill", y="day", hue="sex",
    kind="violin", bw_adjust=.5, cut=0,
);
In[39]:
# modifying the interior
sns.catplot(
    data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill", hue="sex",
    kind="violin", inner="stick", split=True, palette="pastel",
)
Out[39]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x2b3c6b68580>
